{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532306"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:25:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14667"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.11,0.03,0.17,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7360"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43476"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"457"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3644"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17954"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department reporting a five-day history of fever, right upper quadrant pain and nausea. He returned from backpacking in India three weeks ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He works as a software engineer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant with voluntary guarding. There is no jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 135 g/L (130-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 15.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 12.8 x 10^9/L (2.0-7.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 180 U/L (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transferase 65 U/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT scan shows a 6 cm single hypodense lesion in the right lobe of the liver.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely implicated pathogen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Entamoeba histolytica","Schistosoma mansoni","Leishmania donovani","Echinococcus granulosus","Fasciola hepatica"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation strongly suggests an amoebic liver abscess. \u003Cstrong\u003EEntamoeba histolytica\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely pathogen given the patient\u0027s young age, recent travel to an endemic area (India), and the characteristic single large abscess in the right lobe of the liver.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosoma mansoni\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the portal venous system and typically causes periportal fibrosis and portal hypertension rather than discrete liver abscesses. The acute presentation with fever would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmania donovani\u003C/strong\u003E causes visceral leishmaniasis (kala-azar) which presents with hepatosplenomegaly, pancytopenia, and a more chronic course rather than a focal liver abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchinococcus granulosus\u003C/strong\u003E causes hydatid cysts of the liver which are typically asymptomatic and found incidentally. The acute presentation with fever makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasciola hepatica\u003C/strong\u003E (liver fluke) typically causes biliary tract disease with intermittent obstruction and cholangitis. While it can cause liver lesions during its migratory phase, these are typically multiple and track through the liver parenchyma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe single large abscess in the right lobe is particularly characteristic of amoebic liver abscess. The recent travel history to an endemic area makes \u003Cem\u003EE. histolytica\u003C/em\u003E the most likely causative organism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Amoebic liver abscess typically presents with fever and right upper quadrant pain in patients with travel to endemic regions.","Single lesions in the right lobe of the liver are characteristic of amoebic abscess.","Entamoeba histolytica is the causative organism in over 90% of liver abscesses in returning travelers from endemic areas."],"references":["Shirley DT, Farr L, Watanabe K, Moonah S. A Review of the Global Burden, New Diagnostics, and Current Therapeutics for Amebiasis. Open Forum Infect Dis. 2018;5(7):ofy161. Published 2018 Jul 5. doi:10.1093/ofid/ofy161","Roediger R, Lisker-Melman M. Pyogenic and Amebic Infections of the Liver. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2020;49(2):361-377. doi:10.1016/j.gtc.2020.01.013"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43476"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43476","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43476"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T19:58:14+10: